// T0687 (coverage hardening): when a task panics and is awaited from a
// non-coroutine helper, the helper's `<-task` receive must:
//   1. Complete the pump-based spin (WASM) / usleep spin (host),
//   2. Observe `G.panicked == 1` in readyBlk,
//   3. Re-panic so the panic propagates out of the helper to the test harness.
//
// The existing `t0687_await_in_helper_test.pr` covers the success path
// exhaustively, and `panic_recovery_task.pr` covers panic-via-receive but only
// from a coroutine context (`main` is wrapped by wrapMainWithScheduler).
// Neither exercises the combination of (a) panicking goroutine, (b) non-
// coroutine helper await, (c) WASM pump-spin. This snapshot test fills that
// gap on host AND `--target wasm32-wasi`.
//
// Excluded on windows for the same reason as panic_recovery_task.pr (panic
// message routing through the Windows runtime).
panicking_worker() int {
  assert(false, "boom from worker");
  return 0;
}

// Non-coroutine helper that awaits a panicking task. On WASM this exercises
// the new pump-spin path; on host the usleep spin. In both cases the receive
// must re-panic, terminating the process via promise_panic.
helper_await_panicking() int {
  task[int] x = go panicking_worker();
  return <-x;
}

main() `test(expected: "panic: boom from worker", exclude: windows) {
  helper_await_panicking();
  print_line("unreachable — helper should have re-panicked");
}
